<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1059,264,375]" pageId="4" pageNumber="963">
D i a g n o s i s: The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kirsch" authorityYear="1871" box="[468,594,265,286]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="966" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[468,594,265,286]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="963">Aphelocerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
KIRSCH was revised in 2005 (OPITZ 2005). This work included a key to species. 
<taxonomicName box="[534,737,294,315]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="963" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ligulus">
<emphasis box="[534,737,294,315]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="963">Aphelocerus ligulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens key out to 
<emphasis box="[968,1058,294,315]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="963">A. batesi</emphasis>
OPITZ from which 
<taxonomicName box="[346,445,323,345]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="963" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ligulus">
<emphasis box="[346,445,323,345]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="963">A. ligulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens differ by showing shorter phallobasic lobes that are shorter, wider, and more acuminate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1059,390,676]" pageId="4" pageNumber="963">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 4.0 mm; width 2.0 mm. Form: As in 
<figureCitation box="[895,983,390,412]" captionStart="Figs 262-265" captionStartId="93.[151,191,1499,1521]" captionTargetBox="[153,1060,199,1483]" captionTargetId="figure@93.[153,1061,199,1485]" captionTargetPageId="93" captionText="Figs 262-265: Habitus; (262) Aphelocerus copanus; (263) A. ligulus; (264) A. magnipannus; (265) A. nodus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746792" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746792/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="963">Fig. 263</figureCitation>
. Color: Black; row of white setae at base of elytral sutural margin contiguous with anterior patch of white setae, elytral disc posterior patch of white setae minimally developed. Head: Interocular depression and frontal umbo shallow; antenna (
<figureCitation box="[785,851,478,500]" captionStart="Figs 1-27" captionStartId="70.[151,191,1302,1324]" captionTargetBox="[155,1057,207,1268]" captionTargetId="figure@70.[155,1058,207,1283]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="Figs 1-27: Antennae; (1) Aphelocerus nodus; (2) A. copanus; (3) A. magnipannus; (4) A. yoro; (5) A. sparicapillus; (6) A. tigra. (7) A. nolus; (8) A. ligulus; (9) Perilypus schusteri; (10) P. apunctus; (11) P. virgulatus; (12) P. izabal; (13) P. alpinus; (14) Cregya fuscomacula; (15) Phonius versus; (16) Pujoliclerus ariquemes; (17) Pelonium falcatum; (18) Pujoliclerus cnecostus; (19) P. trunculus. (20) P. sentus; (21) P. testudinatus; (22) P. catie; (23) P. flavidus; (24) P. convexus; (25) P. meloinus; (26) P. mexicoensis; (27) P. tuxtlas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746746/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="963">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) capitate, funicular antennomeres filiform, progressively shorter and wider towards capitulum, capitulum compact; eyes finely facetted, eye narrower than frons (EW/FW 16/34). Thorax: Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[265,351,566,588]" captionStart="Figs 101-117" captionStartId="75.[151,191,1477,1499]" captionTargetBox="[152,1030,198,1448]" captionTargetId="figure@75.[152,1030,198,1465]" captionTargetPageId="75" captionText="Figs 101-117: Pronota; (101) Aphelocerus ligulus; (102) A. yoro; (103) Ridica achira; (104) R. merida; (105) Ampleris cacuminis; (106) Plocamocera catalexis; (107) Aphelocerus tigra; (108) A. sparicapillus; (109) A. nolus; (110) A. magnipannus; (111) Pyticeroides desodes; (112) Cregya petalosa; (113) C. livida; (114) C. tobagoensis; (115) C. maura; (116) Pujoliclerus flavidus; (117) Amboakis collucoatis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746756" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746756/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="963">Fig. 101</figureCitation>
) quadrate, very finely punctate; (PW/PL 65/65); elytral disc with two patches of white setae, anterior patch obliquely positioned and oblong, posterior patch very small, disc impressed with small setiferous punctures (EL/EW 200/60). Abdomen: Pygidium transverse 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[359,366,654,676]" pageId="4" pageNumber="963">/</emphasis>
scutiform; aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[629,721,654,676]" captionStart="Figs 201-206" captionStartId="83.[151,191,1264,1286]" captionTargetBox="[153,1059,191,1248]" captionTargetId="figure@83.[153,1059,191,1248]" captionTargetPageId="83" captionText="Figs 201-206: Aedeagi; (201) Aphelocerus copanus; (202) A. ligulus; (203) A. magnipannus; (204) A. nodus; (205) A. nolus; (206) A. sparicapillus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746772" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746772/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="963">Fig. 202.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
